ğŸ§  So, what kind of regex does Logstash use?
âœ… Short Answer:
**Logstash uses Java-style regular expressions, just like Elasticsearch â€” because it runs on the JVM and uses the same underlying Java regex engine.
But it gets even more powerful when you use Grok filters, which are basically named regex patterns built on top of Java regex.
ğŸ§© Breakdown:
1. grok filter plugin (most common regex use in Logstash)
Grok is built entirely on Java regex.
Provides a readable DSL of named patterns like %{IP}, %{DATA}, %{WORD}, etc.
You can also define custom regex patterns.
filter {
  grok {
    match => { "message" => "%{IP:client} %{WORD:method} %{URIPATHPARAM:request}" }
  }
}
Under the hood, the %{IP} expands into a Java regex like:
(?:(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9][0-9]?)(?:\.|$)){4}
âœ… So you're really using Java regex â€” just made friendlier via Grok.
2. regexp in conditionals
You can use raw regex in conditionals too:
if [message] =~ /ERROR.*/ {
  mutate { add_field => { "level" => "error" } }
}
âœ… Again: This is Java regex, so:
Character classes, groups, quantifiers â€” âœ…
Backreferences (\1) â€” âœ…
Lookaheads ((?=...)) â€” âœ…
Lookbehinds ((?<=...)) â€” âœ…
ğŸš¨ BUT: Whether lookbehind is supported depends on the exact Java version running Logstash. Older versions didnâ€™t always handle complex lookbehinds well.
3. mutate, gsub, and other filters
These support regex in substitution too:
mutate {
  gsub => [ "message", "\s+", " " ]
}
Again â€” Java regex flavor.
âœ… Summary: What Regex Does Logstash Use?

Feature	Supported?
Character classes	âœ… Yes
Groups & alternation	âœ… Yes
Quantifiers (+, *)	âœ… Yes
Lookaheads	âœ… Yes
Lookbehinds	âœ… Yes (Java >= 9+, depending on complexity)
Backreferences	âœ… Yes
Named groups	âŒ Not in raw regex, but grok offers named fields
ğŸ”§ TL;DR:
Logstash uses Java regular expressions across its filters, especially:
grok (built on regex)
regexp in conditionals
gsub in mutate filters
ğŸ’¡ If you're using grok, you're working with friendly regex abstractions that expand into gnarly Java regex behind the scenes.
